comment.narrative:
Training for the Ministerial AIDS Coordinators 23-24th February 2016 GICC. There was a sensitization workshop on mainstreaming health, particularly HIV and gender related issues in environmental assessment (EA) in Botswana. The objective of the workshop were: • To understand the link between health, HIV and gender and development projects • To appreciate the benefits of implementing a comprehensive programme for development projects integrating HIV, TB, malaria, and non- communicable diseases for project employees and the receiving communities • To understand the roles of various stakeholders in Environmental Assessment
There were 25participants trained. UNDP developed the workshop evaluation tool and consolidated it after the workshop. The participants highly appreciated the EIA training and the topics covered. They found it to be very informative. Training Workshop in Botswana Masa Square from 9-10 August 2016. One of the key elements of the UNDP/AfDB initiative is to improve the capacity of environmental assessment practitioners (EAPs), and thus the National AIDS Coordinating Agency (NACA), in conjunction with the Botswana EAP Association (BEAPA), organised a training workshop on inclusive Environmental and Social Assessment targeted at BEAPA-registered DEA officials, EIA consultants and social and health impact specialists in Gaborone, Botswana from 9-10 August 2016. The training workshop was carried out by UNDP resourced Consultant Ms Bryony Walmsley of the Southern African Institute for Environmental Assessment (SAIEA). The training workshop aimed to encourage EAPs to conduct more inclusive EIAs, with greater focus on human rights, health and gender (HRHG) through:
• Raising awareness about the scope of HRHG issues; • Providing guidance on best practice for each stage of the EIA process;
